## 2. SCSS class naming

### Root class

Every component gets one root CSS class. Derive it from the component name using these abbreviations:

| Component prefix | CSS prefix |
|-----------------|-----------|
| `Manager_` | `m__` |
| `Editor_` | `e__` |
| `Renderer_` | `r__` |
| `Panel_` | `p__` |
| `Page_` | `pg__` |
| `Component_` | `c__` |
| `Header_` | `h__` |
| `Dialog_` | `d__` |

Then append the domain in kebab-case.

```
Manager_DiseaseProfile  →  .m__disease-profile
Editor_DiseaseProfile   →  .e__disease-profile
Panel_MultiVarList      →  .p__multi-var-list
Renderer_PathwayStateEditor  →  .r__pathway-state-editor
```

The root class is **always a class selector, never an ID**. IDs are reserved for mouse-interactivity pop-up anchors registered with `openContent`.

### Sub-element naming

Use the root class as SCSS nesting root. Sub-elements append `__element` to the root. Nesting handles depth — do not flatten into long chains.

```scss
// Correct — nested, readable
.m__disease-profile {
  .m__disease-profile__selector {
    .m__disease-profile__selector-header { }
    .m__disease-profile__selector-title { }
  }
}

// Wrong — overly deep flat selectors
.manager__disease-profile__disease-variable-data__header__title { }
```

When a sub-element is only meaningful inside its parent block, it can use a shorter contextual name within the nesting:

```scss
.m__disease-profile {
  &__selector { }         // shorthand nesting only when nesting makes context obvious
  &__selector-header { }
}
```

### Modifiers

Use single modifier classes (`.selected`, `.edit-mode`, `.disabled`, `.active`, `.error`). Do not use double-dash BEM modifiers — they're verbose and SCSS nesting already provides context.

```scss
.m__disease-profile__vars__item {
  &.selected { background: C.$secondary-06; }
  &.edit-mode { border-color: transparent; }
}
```

