## 4. Design application pattern — parent scopes children

Library components (`TS_DropDown`, `TS_Input`, `TS_Textarea`, `TS_Tabs`, `TS_Checkbox`, `.ts-prop-renderer`) have no default visual design. They render minimal structure. **The Manager or Page is responsible for applying the design system to its descendant library components.**

Do this by extending `%KM2Design_*` placeholders within the Manager/Page SCSS root scope:

```scss
// Manager_DiseaseProfile.scss
.m__disease-profile {
  .ts-prop-renderer { @extend %KM2Design_PropRenderer; }
  .ts-dropdown     { @extend %KM2Design_DropDown; }
  .ts-input        { @extend %KM2Design_Input; }
  .ts-textarea     { @extend %KM2Design_TextArea; }
  .ts-radio        { @extend %KM2Design_Radio; }
}
```

The `%KM2Design_*` placeholders live in `@app/styles/km2`. Import with:

```scss
@use '@app/styles/km2' as *;
```

Never apply design tokens at the individual child component level — the child component has no knowledge of which design context it lives in. Visual variants across contexts are handled by the parent's SCSS scope.

### consts.scss for shared placeholders within a component family

When a component family (e.g., all tabs inside `Editor_DiseaseProfile`) shares a layout pattern, define it once as a placeholder in `consts.scss` next to the parent:

```scss
// Editor_DiseaseProfile/consts.scss
%DPEditor_TabDesign {
  padding: 24px 0;
  & > .fade-scroll-wrapper__content > .ts-grid {
    column-gap: 48px;
    row-gap: 12px;
    grid-template-columns: max-content 1fr;
  }
}
```

Tab SCSS files then extend it:

```scss
// Editor_DiseaseProfile_General.scss
.e__dp__general {
  @extend %DPEditor_TabDesign;
}
```

