## 13. SCSS specificity — how overrides work

Because all SCSS is global (no CSS modules), specificity is managed by scope. The contract:

- **Library component SCSS** (e.g., `TS_DropDown.scss`) defines the component's structure with low specificity.
- **Application Manager SCSS** applies design via `@extend %KM2Design_*` within its root class scope — higher specificity wins naturally.
- **Never target library internals from an unrelated component scope.** Only override library component classes from your direct ancestor scope.

```scss
// Correct — Manager scopes its dropdown override
.m__disease-profile {
  .ts-dropdown { @extend %KM2Design_DropDown; }
}

// Wrong — reaching into library from unrelated scope
.some-other-component .ts-dropdown { color: red; }
```

When a specific instance needs an override beyond the KM2 design (e.g., a wider dropdown), add a modifier class to the component in TSX and scope the override under it:

```scss
.m__disease-profile {
  .ts-dropdown.variable-dropdown .ts-dropdown__selected { color: C.$primary-01; }
}
```
